On another front, I've just written a historical piece, at the request of the editors of Self & Society, the journal of the Association for Humanistic Psychology in the UK. The title is 'My early engagement with humanistic psychology' and covers the period 1970 to 1985 (see http://www.human-inquiry.com/jhS&Sfinal2.pdf). It launches a new series in the journal on the very early days.

In 1970, humanistic psychology, with its focus on self-actualization, exactly met the needs of the day for change-agents like myself. In 2012, it has long since expanded in my worldview into participatory psychology, with a focus on the need for relational-actualization, learning how to live in a universe of multi-dimensional relational dynamics.

